  </ul>
</div>

<section id="what-comes-next" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Molecule and the Market</h2>
  <p>There are things that could go right. The heterologous expression of lariocidin's biosynthetic gene cluster in <em>Streptomyces lividans</em> opens a genuine path for synthetic biology optimization — the kind of medicinal chemistry work that takes a promising natural product and engineers it into something with the pharmacokinetic profile a drug needs. The identification of dozens of similar biosynthetic gene clusters in bacterial genomes suggests lariocidin is not a one-off curiosity but the entry point to a broader chemical family. If even one member of that family has better bioavailability, easier synthesis, or enhanced potency, the discovery value multiplies.</p>
  <p>CARB-X — the Combating Antibiotic-Resistant Bacteria Biopharmaceutical Accelerator, a public-private partnership funded by BARDA and the Wellcome Trust — exists specifically to bridge the gap between academic discovery and clinical development for exactly this kind of early-stage antibiotic lead. Push incentive models, subscription-based reimbursement schemes, and market entry rewards have been proposed and partially implemented in the UK and Sweden to decouple antibiotic revenue from volume of use. These are real mechanisms. They are also underfunded, geographically limited, and not yet sufficient to replace the commercial infrastructure that major pharmaceutical companies provided before they left.</p>
  <p>Kevin Outterson, executive director of CARB-X, has been saying the quiet part loud for years: "More people are dying from drug-resistant, gram-negative bacterial infections than are dying from HIV. I don't think the world understands that."</p>
  <p>He is right that the world does not understand it. AMR kills without a face. It does not have a ribbon color or a celebrity spokesperson. It kills in ICUs, in post-surgical wards, in the bodies of people who came in for something else and acquired an infection that nothing could treat. It is diffuse, statistical, and invisible until it is personal.</p>
  <p>We now have a molecule — found in a backyard, published in <em>Nature</em>, validated in a mouse model, structurally unprecedented, mechanistically novel, and active against pathogens that have defeated every other option — that represents the first genuinely new antibiotic class lead since 1987. Gerry Wright's team at McMaster did the science. The science is real.</p>
  <p>Whether lariocidin ever reaches a patient depends less on the science than on whether anyone is willing to pay for it. The discovery happened in a backyard in Hamilton, Ontario. The failure, if it comes, will happen in a boardroom.</p>
</section>

